			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">AE Kiting: Getting that circle started<a name="48763"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jun 28 04 1:57 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Up until recently, all of my soloing as been through swarm kiting.  Now, as our bard charm's level cap becomes relevant, I find myself wanting to try something new.  So, having read all these posts about AE kiting and autocircling, I decided to give it a try.
<br />

<br />
After spending a little time in The Grey testing it out, this is what my early impressions are.
<br />

<br />
A big part of autocircling seems to be finding the proper run speed for mobs in question.  I almost feel like I should be carrying every possible drum mod.  For example, I tried AE kiting the golems and shissar around the temple in the Grey.  Originally, I tried with Selo's Drum, which seemed to be far too fast.  The mobs couldn't catch me but only DDD would hit as it seems to have a slightly larger radius.  Finally, I switched to a Hand Drum (yeah, the original store bought one) and the mobs were just out of reach but always in range of all 3 AE's.
<br />

<br />
Starting up the autocircle takes a great deal of precision.  The first few times I tried this, I only pulled 3 or 4 mobs.  And it would seems that as long as I was travelling at the proper speed, I could just start up in a circle anywhere and while I would get hit a few times when the bunched up mobs caught up, after that 1 round of combat they would be unable to catch me and the circle was fine for the rest of the pull.  However, it was very apparent that as you pull more mobs, you no longer have the luxury of taking a few hits before getting the circle right.
<br />

<br />
Does anyone have any tips for how to start up that initial autocircle without getting hit by the mobs chasing you?  What I've been doing is panning out as far as I can in 3rd person view and making a big circle and slowly tightening down, but the problem is if I turn just a little too tight at any point I get the whole bunch in my face and it's time to hit deftdace while I'm stunned :p.
<br />

<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%"><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=1054297">Kalerana</a><br>
